  "response": "# Diagnosis\n\n**Finding:** `crime_00010` — *Timezone Roulette* at `src/date.ts:29,33` (`timezone_unsafe_parse`).\n\n**Responsible literal:** `\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` on line 29.\n\nPer the ES spec, an ISO date‑time string with no zone designator is parsed in the **host's local time**. In CI the host is UTC, so the literal resolves to `2026-12-25T07:00:00Z` and the promo‑open check matches what the test author had in mind. In production, a European host (e.g. CET = UTC+1) parses the same literal as `2026-12-25T06:00:00Z` — earlier in absolute time, which flips the gate open before the intended moment for any user whose local clock has already crossed the threshold. (The companion literal `\"2026-12-20\"` on line 33 is a *date‑only* form, which the spec parses as UTC, so it isn't the culprit.)\n\n# Smallest change\n\nAppend `Z` to make the zone explicit — no function signature changes, no library swap, one character of diff:\n\n```ts\n// src/date.ts:29\n- new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")\n+ new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\")\n```\n\nThis pins the promo opening to the same UTC instant the CI test was implicitly assuming, so prod behaviour collapses back to CI behaviour for every host timezone.",
